< review>
Pros:
-Landscaping is very well maintained
-Plenty of areas for people with children to get in some physical activity
-large area to go jogging, walk your pet, or take someone to go walking with you

Cons:
-very limited parking
-roaches
-inside of apartments are old and not up to date
-roaches
-Tulare entrance to complex is always crowded
-roaches

This place, and like many other places, has its goods and bads. I loved the large area on the south end of the complex because you can go jogging, walk your dog, or take someone with you to walk and talk and it was great. But then on the inside of the apartments you have old cupboards, bad wall sockets, and an endless supply of roaches. I would clean the counter tops one day and wake up the next day with roach legs, egg sacks, and roach droppings everywhere. Pest control was called plenty of times but they spray the corners of the unit and leave within 10 mins. You won‚Äôt be living with them, they will be living with you. Also, parking is pretty bad. If you do not get a parking spot close to your unit before it hits 7-8 pm, you will be parking 1/4 mile down the complex or having to exit the complex and park across the street in the residential area. Torrey ridge will be a good place to live if they deal with the roach and parking problems.</review>

I always forget to get the names of the workers who do a good job but I came in around 5pm and one of the workers said he was new, well he was very polite and he deserves the recognition for being a lovely batista!! He also made an amazingly delicious Mocha. I plan on coming back more often as I live in the area now.<//Review>

< Rate>
5</Rate>
<text>I have to stop here every time I'm in mammoth.  Hey, last time I went to mammoth, I went simply to stop here!   Their staff is always friendly and welcoming and they are doing a fantastic job of making everyone feel safe during this COVID19 stuff.

The lattes are great, they make some of their own syrups and non dairy milks are available if you're in to it.   Last time i visited I grabbed an iced chai.  The batista made it nice and spicy; just the way I like it!   I wish I could remember her name.

The real winner here is their cold brew.   They use that gorgeous, science experiment  looking drip system.  It produces a far superior product compared to most coffee shops' bag in water method.

They have multiple options for beans to go, and they'll grind them for you if you need it.

Thank you guys for being such a consistent, reliable, and tasty stop!<//text><Pictures>None</Pictures><response>None<//response><Gmap_id>0x80960dcbc012429b:0xf925d79cb57880de</Gmap_id></record>

<Date>1482532467367< /Date><rate>5</rate><review>Coffee for anyone who writes, calls himself/herself a writer, reads books, reviews books and engenders a love for them is more often than not ‚Äúon coffee.‚Äù  One who is traveled knows happiness is sometimes obscured in the minutia of life, measured in mm found hot in non-neutral cups at BVK.

We visited BVK quite consistently over the course of three weeks in Mammoth Lakes. Coffee is roasted "in house" and the handcrafted waffles (similar to Belgian waffles) were superb.  Daily our adventure was ripe with cappuccino and sublime smells of cinnamon, espresso and glimpses of Matt's hand built espresso machines.

Our family even brought a bag of BVK home for others to try. If in town do seek the ambrosia found at Black Velvet Coffee. BVK libations are an exceptional value, spilling over with quality and atmosphere in Hipster heaven. Thank you Hammer family and the barista team for hot happiness in a cup!< /review><pictures>None<//pictures>< Response>

115381807827289327093<//UserId.>
< user_name>
eric moss<//user_name>
<Time>1413161157089</Time>< rate>
4<//rate>
< review>
I had very good service there, with baristas willing and able to talk coffee-nerd talk.  Their beans were good and fresh, and the extractions on their Synesso were consistent.  The vanilla latte was too sweet for my taste, but another double-shot fixed that up nicely.  I'd raise the brew temp another degree for the beans they were using, but that's personal preference (the extraction was bright but not sour).  I didn't get a chance to try their cold drip or pourover coffees.  They carry Fevertree lemon soda, which is great find (the Ginger Ale is famous, but IMO Blenheim's Red Hot is head and shoulders above everything else).  That was a great complement to the munchies from Bleu just down the block.  The atmosphere is that of a modern industrial shop vs hippy vs homey vs sophisticated wood-grain shop.  I like them all if the coffee is good, which was the case here when I came through -- I went there every day.<//review>

< review>
Nom. I went to the Mission Community Farmers Market. First table I passed a guy was holding out a sample of some kind of baked good. Below him was a spread of heavenly looking edibles. I'm not a foodie, and I was only planning on getting produce so this was unexpected. I looked at the guy and told him thanks, but I'm trying not to eat gluten. He said that's good because his stuff was all gluten free and pointed to the giant sign behind him. I tried the sample and it was delicious. He asked if I wanted to try something else, so I had something chocolate and I was sold. I bought two muffing things, one was lemon and chocolate and the other was chocolate and something. They weren't cheap, but man oh man they are good. And beautiful. If you want some gourmet gluten free baked goods this bakery is amazing.<//review>

<Review>Gluten-free bakery. Slightly pricey, but we had lunch for two for $20.

Their iced tea was fantastic. I had one with "African" in the name, and it was flowery, maybe a Rooibos blend. $2 refills are a little prohibitive, though.

The bread was good for gluten-free. The white-bread analog we had had a dense texture like a cornmeal cake, and the flavor was unobtrusive. Both my wife and I got our sinuses singed on the horseradish mustard used on our sandwiches, so if you don't like spicy mustard, maybe ask them to go light on that.

We did not try anything sweet, but the presentation was very strong, and I was sorely tempted by a molasses cookie.< /Review></record>

This bakery has a great selection, all gluten free,  and everything has tasted exceptional. There's only been two things I didn't like from here: the Kalamata olive round(which had a bit too much salt for my taste) the Linzer torte(which tastes more like an olive oil cake than a browned butter torte). < Review>
So a friend of mine dragged me to this place... She introduced me to the Chef Brian and told me to trust him. I have been told that if I don't like poke from other places I may still like it here. However, I didn't even know what poke was. I typically stick to what I know I like and I also avoid fish for the most part... I then decided to take the leap of faith and try something outside of my comfort zone. So, I let Brian guide me in my ordering process. Not only did he ask my likes and dislikes, but he gauged my excitement and tailored a cocktail of a poke bowl just for me.

I took my order to-go to avoid disrespecting the chef with the face of a skeptic and a disappointed customer. My roommate assured me that if I didn't like it she would gladly assist me in dealing with the left overs... As she was staring at my food like she hadn't eaten in weeks.

The outcome not only surprised me, but it woke taste buds that I had apparently been starving from a flavor profile like I had never know. Needless to say I am now a fan of Pok√©Motto and Chef Brian. If you gain any wisdom from my experience I hope that you trust the chef.</Review>

< userid>
105664270081403524546< /userid>
<user_name>Albert Lee< /user_name><date>1545922874355<//date>< rating>
5<//rating>
< Review>
Despite the name, this is not your average poke spot.  Serving high quality sushi omakase (Chef's choice - a prix fixe menu curated nightly) by reservation only Thurs - Sun evenings, be sure to grab your spot at the chef's table! They order an appropriate amount of fresh fish for every omakase session so understandably, impromptu guests cannot be added same day. This is a very memorable, intimate experience and I highly recommend trying it out.

No omakase dining session is alike, since unique fish are ordered seasonally, and the chefs are one of a kind masters of cuisine and entertainment. All the strangers I met the night I went agreed not only was it an amazing meal, they could have charged a cover fee for the laughs as well.

I've tasted some of the best sushi I've ever had at PokeMotto not only due to the quality served, but because the chefs take the time to select exquisite types of fish and at different ages as well. Chef Brian narrates your meal as he preps an artisanal experience, touching upon the intricacies of the fish he selects and how he achieves umami goodness with every plate served.

I was blown away by the creative dishes varying from the simple to complex, sometimes pairing ingredients or technique to bring out the best flavor of each course. Chef Sang adds even more variety to the table by utilizing a different approach to his dishes and together they balance the dining experience perfectly.  They really understand their audience without making things pretentious.

With decades of experience under both of their belts, Chef Brian & Sang are animated and eager to cater to your tastebuds. I've been to a lot of high-end sushi establishments in the L.A. area and PokeMotto easily puts them to shame without breaking the bank.

Oh, and the poke bowls are pretty awesome too. Not only are they reasonably priced, they taste amazing and it shows - all the locals love this place so it can get pretty busy during lunch and dinner prime time. Order ahead online or get something delivered. Whether you go for poke or omakase, you won't be disappointed.  Fresh ingredients and quality fish paired eloquently with flair result in an epic meal every time.</Review>

< Text>
Had a late night dinner at the Brass Rail a couple nights ago and I was so delighted with my meal I had to write a review. The bacon cheese burger was amazing, the meat is super high grade, the bun was soft and delicious, even the veggies were on point (proper Roma tomatoes not grainy watered down beefsteaks and fresh crispy lettuce and onion). The honey sriracha chicken wings had me in a state of food bliss. Undoubtedly the best burger and wings you can get within an hours drive in any direction. This place is a must try if you have not already made the stop. I am so thankful to have this option in our town.</Text>

The staff helped me figure out the best treatment plan for me based on my needs and my wallet.

A full replacement of my upper teeth was more expensive than I really wanted to pay but once I compared the cost of mini implants to regular implants, I was convinced it was worth it. I decided on the nicest material because I really wanted them to look natural and stay with me for a long time.

The process wasn‚Äôt perfectly easy, there was some problems with my temporary bite and it caused some extra visits. My temporary broke on Christmas Eve and I called the answering service. Someone met me at the office within 30 minutes and spent hours fixing my temporary and ensuring that I could eat Christmas dinner with my family. It was a huge deal to me. I chose sedation for the initial procedure and it was way easier than I thought it would be. Pain was minimal after the procedure was done on Saturday I was back at work on Monday.

After about 6 weeks from the start I have the kind of teeth that people notice and make comments about. Teeth that I can actually eat with. I am so proud of my new smile and I actually open my mouth to talk.

Anyone can write a review about their dentist but Its impossible for me to express exactly what this process has done for me and how well I have been treated by everyone at Dr.  Smith‚Äôs office. I still get emotional just thinking about where I started and where I am now after just a couple of months.

<review>The food, vibe and customer service was mediocre and I do not recommend.

I want to praise the great customer service and attention that server Alex gave us while there.

My boyfriend and I sat ourselves and the whole time we were there, Justin who was supposed to be the "assigned" server, NEVER checked on us, brought us anything, or took our order.

Instead, we were served and attended by Alex. While Alex was serving me, I hear Justin calling out to him in a condescending manner and ordering him around while Alex was busy attending other guests. This was very rude and disrespectful to do in front of customers.

The whole time we were there, I overheard Justin tell other guests multiple times how he was glad that he had a server to help (referring to Alex), as if Justin was Alex's master. Very rude and unprofessional.

At the end, I went up to the owner named Jose and explained to him the situation to which all I heard from him was a "thank you and sorry for the inconvenience". Entry dessert display and sales counter are the hook.
Decor, atmosphere, flow of table seating and bar area are the line leading you to the Oceanside deck where continued decor and atmosphere are the sinker.
I'm in!

Host, server, owner were all attentive and friendly.
Menu is extensive.
Quiche was to die for. Gorgeous. Flavorful. not America's typical shaken and stirred pie. This was layers of whole spinach, fresh sauteed mushrooms topped with gooey thickness of cheese resting in a no-crumb-left-behind pie crust.

Husband's burger on toasted brioche was perfection.

The dessert tray was successful at inviting to even the most full stomachs to eat just a little bit more our selections were tough, dry, weak flavor.

I liked C'est La Vie so much that I feel bad giving a review of less than 5 stars.
We vacationed in Laguna Beach. I feel familiarity with a restaurant and therefore, reviews need to be based on more than one meal.

A must go.< /Text><Rate>4< /Rate>< Time>
1512917746731</Time>

Nice french restaurant in this chic Laguna beach area.
There is a bakery up front and seating inside as well as on the patio.
I recommend the patio seating for some amazing views of the ocean!
The food was pretty good, the service was good - the dessert was absolutely divine. Especially the macaroons.</Text>

<Date>1583275633482</Date><gmapID>0x80dce5b549b136b5:0xf8e0c73b80b29a02< /gmapID><username>Natural VeganGuy< /username>< review>
while this place is not vegan, the chef will work with you to make your experience memorable. We came as a group and, given the French theme, I had little expectations for a vegan menu. I planned on grabbing a drink and perhaps a salad; they offered a large plate of sauteed seasonal vegetables which were done beautifully. The rest of the group was more than happy with the menu selection and the varieties of pastries offered from the in-house bakery.  The deck overlooking the water is one of the best in the area. This is a great place for a birthday or celebration and it lacks the pretentiousness that would normally be associated with a restaurant with a location. The owner is very personable and involved. Faredeh checked in often to see if everything was OK (given the search for vegan options). She was awesome!  I'll certainly be back<//review>

I love it here. Not as pretentious as many popular Laguna spots. It's got a wonderful rooftop patio with a great view of main beach. The food has never let us down, the drinks are great. The prices a touch high and the service is just okay...but I absolutely love going and sitting outside. You cant go wrong with the breakfast menu, but I also highly recommend the salmon/rice.<//Review>

Went for New Years day lunch because Nick's had a two hour wait.  Waiting for about ten minutes until we motioned someone over for drinks.  The cocktails we had were the highlight of the trip.  The $20 burger we had was dry.  Asked server for ketchup, luckily the table next to us had some from the last group and was nice enough to hand it over after hearing our frustration.  We never got any ketchup, server probably noticed that our neighbors gave us some.  Fish and chips was average.  The pistachio macaroon was also very well done, rest were ok.  It was $85 for the whole meal for three after two drinks and dessert with two $20 mains.< /review>

< review>
The view was awesome! I enjoyed sipping on a latte on the balcony while waiting for our food. The espresso is Lavazza which was very good! They also had milk alternatives. The milk froth was not spectacular but it was acceptable.

As far the food goes it was alright. Nothing out of this world but not bad. We both had omelettes. The bakery items looked great but we were too full to try them.

What is worth raving about is the service! We went in at around 11am on a Wednesday and were served right away. Our server was Justin. He was super friendly and made us feel like a local.

We would go back for the views and the great service.< /review>

Michael Blazina<//Name>
< text>
The view from the upstairs terrace here is magnificent. If you're looking for a nice place to have lunch and see the ocean on a pretty day, it's hard to beat. My seafood quiche wasn't quite as spectacular as the veiw. The crust was overcooked and tough, and the filling, although pretty good, wasn't particularly flavorful. The salad that came with it was very nice, but quite dry, to the point where I needed to request extra dressing. It's hard for me to say how much of this was due to the particular day that I went there vs how much is just the way the restaurant chefs prepare the food. I would definitely give this place another go!<//text>

<username>T B</username>< resp>
None<//resp>
<Review>This place has a French themed but you can order from a variety on the menu. The atmosphere is comfortable and inviting to start; add Faredeh to the mix and you will feel right at home. This sort of personal involvement and care from the owner is rare in the restaurant experience these days! If you are a fan of French Bakeries, be prepared. you are greeted with some amazing pastries the moment you walk in. Just beyond that is the dining area with some great window seating for some world class people watching. There is a small and intimate bar reminiscent of an old world experience. If you are looking for a view, the deck overlooking the ocean is a highlight worth the trip in itself.  Wine selection is decent and their prices are very reasonable given the setting. This is a great place to start a day or wind down in the evening. The central location is perfect for either a beach day or a day exploring the shops and studios. TIP: There are a few parking spaces out back if you are fortunate enough to get one while it's empty</Review></record>

<user>114460173661174493028< /user><Name>Nancy</Name>< Date>
1622685252802<//Date>
<rating>3< /rating>< text>
I've visited this restaurant since the late 1980's, about 30 years.
Since I live in the San Gabriel Valley, I usually go every few months or years.
The dishes that I have ordered have been good or excellent, 4 to 5 stars.  The service used to be very good, but now it is lacking.
That is why I rated it 3 stars.

I went on 11/10/18.  There is a sign which says to seat yourself.
I sat on the patio and picked up a menu that was already on the table.  Someone greeted me at the table and said that he would send a waiter. I was waiting for quite a while (didn't time it, but too long).  I noticed a couple arrived, sat down, and a waiter immediately went to their table and took their order.  He was tall, had an accent and was left-handed, which I noticed because I'm also a lefty.  I say this so that perhaps a manager reading this will identify him and speak to him in order to improve.
I almost walked out, but another waiter came to serve me.  Perhaps because I was alone, they thought I wasn't as important to serve.  A couple of years ago, I also received inferior service to those around me, I feel because I was alone.  This wasn't the case many years ago.

As far as the food, the Sea Bass with chipotle sauce that I had  was excellent.  However, to make the experience enjoyable, as it should be,
the service needs major improvement.
Other reviewers have stated this need just recently on Trip Advisor, etc.
The management should take note and make improvements.< /text>

<GmapID>0x80dce5b549b136b5:0xf8e0c73b80b29a02<//GmapID><userid>117900817344019711276< /userid>< Review>
First impression was a very cute and aesthetically pleasing atmosphere. But the hostess and the busser were arguing about where my boyfriend and I should be seated. They were both telling us to sit at different tables.

The food wasn't absolutely terrible. I'm sure the crepes are good. But I didn't get a crepe. I ordered an omelette. It was supposed to be a southwestern-style spicy omelette, but what they brought me was the avocado and bacon omelette. Which I didn't really complain about because I was actually considering ordering that one, but it was very undercooked and watery inside. It was pretty gross. It was also confusing because two different people came to take our order at different times. The iced mocha was okay, but a little chalky.

What I did love was the violin guy walking around the dining room. He stopped at our table and played for a long time. Which was sweet and kinda romantic-y, but I guess we just weren't really sure how to act (should we just watch him play and smile, continue talking to each other, etc.) or if it was appropriate to tip him.

Overall it was a bit of a disappoinment and we felt a little like we had wasted our time and money üôÅ It probably could have been better, but that wasn't our experience.< /Review>

<Time>1533526097230< /Time>< Rating>
3< /Rating>
< Text>
We had a credit voucher to use at this restaurant so we have it a shot one evening. The view from the upstairs patio is great, especially at sunset. Sadly that was best part of the evening. The food was good, however it was not great. And our server was slow. Three other tables were seated after we arrived and left before we had received our check. The staff is really friendly though, so if you are not in any rush, it could be ok. The deciding factor for us not to return was the price of the desserts. The macaroons are $2.45 each. Our desserts, chocolate cheesecake and a tiramisu we just under $12 each. Again, both were good, but not rave worthy.<//Text>

<rate>5<//rate>< review>
Many years back, my mom and I ate here on the fly--it was fabulous. The service was lovely and so was the coffee. A few years later I remembered this place when a friend of mine was getting married on the beach The manager was SO accommodating--she allowed me to come in  prior to the ceremony and reserve a long table with an amazing view. I brought in fresh flowers and place settings for each seat to surprise the couple and a small group of guests for their post ceremony dinner here. The manager was amazingly sweet and helpful, and from what I hear, the meal was superb. I never got to go back in and say thank you; I have since moved out of state. I will make it a point to eat here on my next visit to Laguna.< /review>

<text>I really enjoyed my dish of the pasta mamma. I thought it was light yet hearty in a delicious, satisfying way. There wasn't too much Alfredo sauce, there was the perfect amount of eggs, bacon and the tomatoes on top sealed the deal. Absolutely delicious.

I tried the banana foster crepe which was sweet and satisfying as well. The view if you choose outside seating is gorgeous and I enjoyed eying their decor.

What brought down the rating for this place was the waiter. I'd hate to put so much emphasis on the staff, because we're there to eat. However, I feel that waiters/waitresses/ hostesses do make a difference. In this case, it was our waiter. The host who helped us to our table was very sweet and polite upon arriving and departing.

For starters, the waiter did not supply us with any bread. Everyone around us received it, except us until we asked for it. He took our order, then later returned with our food. Now we were celebrating my friends birthday, who specifically told us we had to try her sweet potato fries when they arrived. She told us before she even ordered it, as she was the only one who had been to this establishment before. The waiter then appeared with the food and asked if everything looked okay. The birthday girl mentioned she had ordered sweet potato fries, not the fries she was given. He immediately got defensive and said "you said steak fries." She said okay it's alright I will eat them. He then asked if she would like potato fries and she said no thank you. She was clearly upset. He said "are you sure?" as if he was annoyed. I jumped in and said yes, she would like her sweet potato fries.

This in my opinion was unacceptable. This could've been easily labeled as a miscommunication and resolved. First, apologize to the customer and then politely inform them you will correct the order and bring them out as soon as possible. It's really not that hard. He was just a bad waiter over all and really brought down the mood.</text>< pictures>

I don't usually do restaurant reviews, but this place was truly terrible!!!! My friend and I were looking for a place to relax and to study. It was empty, and the busboy (who was very nice) told us we were welcome to have a cup of coffee and study since the restaurant was empty. The waiter, however, was very rude and made us feel extremely uncomfortable; he constantly tried to push us to buy more food and to buy alcoholic drinks, and then made snide remarks under his breath about us being cheap when we said no thank you. The food was terrible!!!! He gave us dry, stale bread, but the busboy was nice enough to get us something a little fresher. The food that we ordered was really salty and not very fresh looking, and the dipping sauces looked gross and smelled funky. Then he charged us $30 for a single appetizer and two coffees. We didn't even get a refill for our coffee because he left for a smoke break and was gone for a while. The menu said that the appetizer was only $10 and that the coffee was $3, but he said that was his "special" rate with a really mean smile. ***It is not worth the nice view to go here; please don't support these people after they bullied and ripped us off***< /Text>

<user_name>Yvette Lopez</user_name><pics>None< /pics>< Review>
Not sure how to feel about this place. Arrived to an early Valentine's day dinner and were offered anywhere to sit by young man at bar. We chose a table with ocean view. We were told to please move to a smaller table adjacent to that table because the table by window was reserved for a larger party. We abided. Service was great by our server. Very attentive. Food was very good. We noticed during our meal, another couple came in and were told the same thing as us....they could sit anywhere they'd like. They looked around, like we did earlier, and chose the exact same table with ocean view. They were escorted to table. They were also a party of 2. They were not told to move (they didn't have reservation). I dont know why we were not allowed to stay at that table and they were. It was our 26th anniversary, chose this place over ALL our choices in Laguna. We chose to eat an early dinner to beat the crowds and maybe get an ocean view. We felt very uncomfortable during our meal because of this. Again, our server was awesome, the cioppino was great and we bought a few desserts at the front little bakery to take home, the young girl helping us was great. We actually ended up eating our cheesecake slice we bought there, instead of waiting till we got back to our hotel. Our server was gracious enough to bring us plates and forks. Just got a feeling we weren't very welcomed there by the way we were treated by that bartender/young man. We tried to still have a romantic dinner. Was a little difficult as we could hear the couple next to us admire the ocean view, that we had, out loud. Would have been a 5 star experience. How does one take that?<//Review>

<name>Yvette Lopez<//name><text>Not sure how to feel about this place. Arrived to an early Valentine's day dinner and were offered anywhere to sit by young man at bar. We chose a table with ocean view. We were told to please move to a smaller table adjacent to that table because the table by window was reserved for a larger party. We abided. Service was great by our server. Very attentive. Food was very good. We noticed during our meal, another couple came in and were told the same thing as us....they could sit anywhere they'd like. They looked around, like we did earlier, and chose the exact same table with ocean view. They were escorted to table. They were also a party of 2. They were not told to move (they didn't have reservation). I dont know why we were not allowed to stay at that table and they were. It was our 26th anniversary, chose this place over ALL our choices in Laguna. We chose to eat an early dinner to beat the crowds and maybe get an ocean view. We felt very uncomfortable during our meal because of this. Again, our server was awesome, the cioppino was great and we bought a few desserts at the front little bakery to take home, the young girl helping us was great. <date>1534972797063< /date><rate>4< /rate>< Pictures>

< Text>
It was great to have the lunch on the patio, we had a really nice time in this restaurant. I had a great ahi ahi ni√ßoise salad, my wife had the croque monsieur (lots of meat inside, ham or turkey, I don't remember), and my in-laws took the beef filet mignon and fish and chips. All plates were tasty and well prepared.
The raspberry cheesecake was also really good. Espresso was also really good, reminded me the ones I used to have in France.
Also, I thought that the prices were in acceptable range with several plates for less than $20.
The only thing that I did not like was the Walnut tart. I was expecting a crunchier one but had a 'soft' one.</Text>

<review>The food at C'est La Vie was very special.. 5 star. I ordered simple, a Tuna Salad sandwich on rye and was I ever surprised. The sandwich was delicious, the bread was fantastic (light and great texture), then they served a pasta salad (which came with it). Best pasta salad I have ever had.

I met and congratulated the cook (Daniel), he happened to come out of the kitchen for a short time. Additionally, the waitstaff was great and the atmosphere is pleasant.

They also have a great patio overlooking Main Beach Park and the ocean. I love this place.

Note: I would give C'est La Vie a 5 star review  except the manager was very rude (before this writing I asked several people about the restaurant and the young manager (35 ish); every single one said he is rude), This manager certainly could work on his friendliness and be more professional with his customers. On the otherhand, the owner is an older man, he and his sister were very nice. Should be 5 Stars for sure!

By:
cmilton111

<Review>My friend and I tried C'est La Vie, yesterday for dinner, using a Travelzoo voucher.  We were not sure what to expect after reading the reviews.  We were very pleasantly surprised.  The manager was very attentive and made sure the server was told about us as soon as we sat down.  He came by several times during the meal to make sure everything was to our liking.

We sat on the covered part of the outside patio.  The forecast had been for rain, but the sun came out.  It was lovely and very comfortable.

Our server was very attentive to us as well as were all the other servers as they walked by---taking empty dishes and filling our water glasses, etc..

The food was delicious!  We had Jumbo Mushrooms with crab for an appetizer.  I had Sea Bass and he had Seafood Fettuccine for the main course.  My friend is from NYC and we have not found any restaurant in OC that he considers as having very good food.  This is the first restaurant that we have found  that he said has very good food!!!

The food is pricey as it is in most French restaurants. Because we were using a Travelzoo voucher, we were very pleased with our experience in every way!</Review></record></dataset><record>

<Gmap_id>0x80dce5b549b136b5:0xf8e0c73b80b29a02<//Gmap_id><response>None< /response><review>Some people meet God standing atop the Grand Canyon; some on the battlefield. I can say that divine intervention appeared before me when glorious beef bourguignon from the Friday french night menu, prepared in an entirely new way (to me), at my command, paired with a deliciously-bodied EnRoute Far Niente.

Prime steak and chops night. Fearsome words only rivaled by "ecstasy" and "heaven" - these are the descriptive modifiers that transformed my evening from the mundane to.... a trip to C'est la Vie.

From perfected dishes presented in front and a wise sommelier filling my glass from behind, I was regaled with tales of truth, and, (I hope) fantastical myth describing the origins of my meal.

Excellence was demonstrated in my presence and I couldn't be more satiated, body and soul.</review>< username>

< Name>
Kevin Dang<//Name>
<Date>1455432997845<//Date><rating>2<//rating>< Review>
Come for the seating next to beach, but don't come for the food. Took my wife here for her birthday and we were expecting French cuisine. The menu is French enough having many of the traditional items. I ordered a Ahi Tartarte for appetizer and it was underwhelming both in looks and taste, not to mention the brown, spotted avocados.

For our entree, wife had the Canard A L'Orange and I had the Entrecote with the ubiquitous peppercorn creme sauce. The duck was soggy and overcooked, tasted like day(s) old food. My ribeye was a fat, sloppy cut, a bit undercooked, but the sauce was a sweet, tangy mess with no peppercorns anywhere. It felt like the chef cooks whatever/however he wanted and haven't read the menu. We were so disappointed with the food we didn't even finish it and decided to pay and leave.

The service was decent enough, but will not be coming back nor recommend any friends to come.<//Review>

< Text>
My wife and I ate dinner at C'est La Vie on Monday February 8, 2010.  The meal was excellent, reasonably priced and complimented by courteous staff and our waitress was extremely attentive and friendly.

We had walked down from our hotel (which had recommended the restaurant), we had the half price bottle of wine with our meal as we understand in California it is OK to Drink and Walk and there was no pressure on us to drink up and leave!

We took dessert back to the hotel with us from their bakery as we were agreeably stuffed!

I had read the mixed reviews before we went and as the negative ones were largely emotional rants and not objectively qualified, both my wife and I are pleased that we ignored them.

It appears the previous reviewer Devo's guest/date/spouse should be pleased if not relieved that they didn't give him a second beer as Valentine's Day is the 14th not the 13th!<//Text>
